Rating: 4
I was inspired to try this recipe because I love a similar recipe by Mark Bittman from the NY Times (less/different peppers, more coffee, red wine). After trying it straight once, I made some modifications that I found on the whole favorable: used a slow cooker on medium for six hours and fully immersed the meat, added a cup of red wine, dry pan toasted the peppers before soaking, subbed a Guajillo pepper (contra the cook from San Antonio del Mar, these are usually less sweet and spicier than Anchos, though YMMV), and doubled the garlic and the syrup. Reduced the sauce on the stove after cooking and then added it back overnight to separate and remove the fat. In the end, I preferred the subtlety of the Bittman recipe to either variant of this recipe, but this is still great and Ill probably make it again, in part because the leftover sauce can be used as a great accent to lots of other dishes. I second the recommendation to put a dollop of sour cream (with or without lime juice/zest added) on the side, to cut the heat, vary the tasting experience, and add to the visual appeal of the presentation. Goes great with mashed potatoes or polenta. Fresh cilantro is a good choice for color, sautéed Portobello (garlic and oil) adds a third flavor/texture that I liked. My last batch I split into half short ribs and half pork spareribs (in cuts of three). Though the beef has the more interesting look/texture, pork works quite well with the flavors here, maybe even better, and is a great alternative for those who are trying to save money or dont eat beef.

