Rating: 4
This recipe needed additional chiles. The ancho chile is very bitter and needs to be offset by another, sweeter chile. I reduce the number of anchos to 3, added 2 guajillo chiles, 2 more garlic cloves, a pinch of cumin, 2 cloves and about a one-inch piece of mexican cinnamon to the other items to be blended. I ommitted the lime juice, its acidity would tend to clash with the chiles in my experience. I did NOT use the soaking liquid from the chiles, the ancho makes it far too bitter. If you want to use soaking liquid in the braise, then soak the guajillos separately from the anchos. I used dried chipotles instead of canned because they're available here. The adobo clashes with the other ingredients and dried chipotles have a much stronger smoky flavor. I used a little beef broth instead of the soaking liquid or water. Also, I simmered them, tightly covered, in a dutch oven on top of the stove instead of the oven, the results were the same as baking and more traditionally Mexican. A lot of Mexicans don't even have ovens. I've been studying Mexican cuisine for years, this is a fairly typical dish with the exception of the addition of the maple syrup, here most would use piloncillo instead. I used the maple syrup, I liked the taste. If you can't find Guajillo chiles in your area, you can substitute New Mexico or California chiles with almost the same result. Another hint for those who don't want a lot of heat: soak your chiles in water with about 3 TB of vinegar added, that will cut the spiciness of the chiles, though any recipe with chipotle in it is going to be spicy by nature.

